import sys

class Solver:
    def solve(self, problem, **kwargs):
        # Increase recursion limit for deeper searches
        sys.setrecursionlimit(10000)
        adj_matrix = problem["adj_matrix"]
        weights = problem["weights"]
        n = len(weights)

        # Build neighbor bitmasks and degree list
        neighbor_masks = [0] * n
        degrees = [0] * n
        for i in range(n):
            mask = 0
            deg = 0
            for j, val in enumerate(adj_matrix[i]):
                if val:
                    mask |= 1 << j
                    deg += 1
            neighbor_masks[i] = mask
            degrees[i] = deg

        # Initial greedy solution for bounding
        order = list(range(n))
        order.sort(key=lambda i: weights[i] / (1 + degrees[i]), reverse=True)
        best_weight = 0
        best_set_mask = 0
        greedy_mask = 0
        greedy_weight = 0
        for i in order:
            if not (neighbor_masks[i] & greedy_mask):
                greedy_mask |= 1 << i
                greedy_weight += weights[i]
        best_weight = greedy_weight
        best_set_mask = greedy_mask

        # Branch-and-bound DFS
        def dfs(candidate_mask, current_weight, chosen_mask):
            nonlocal best_weight, best_set_mask

            # Compute upper bound: sum of all remaining weights
            rem_sum = 0
            rem = candidate_mask
            while rem:
                lb = rem & -rem
                idx = lb.bit_length() - 1
                rem_sum += weights[idx]
                rem ^= lb

            # Prune if cannot beat best
            if current_weight + rem_sum <= best_weight:
                return

            # If no candidates, update best
            if candidate_mask == 0:
                if current_weight > best_weight:
                    best_weight = current_weight
                    best_set_mask = chosen_mask
                return

            # Pick candidate with maximum weight
            cm = candidate_mask
            max_v = -1
            max_w = -1
            while cm:
                lb = cm & -cm
                idx = lb.bit_length() - 1
                w = weights[idx]
                if w > max_w:
                    max_w = w
                    max_v = idx
                cm ^= lb

            v = max_v
            bit_v = 1 << v

            # Branch: include v
            dfs(candidate_mask & ~neighbor_masks[v] & ~bit_v,
                current_weight + weights[v],
                chosen_mask | bit_v)
            # Branch: exclude v
            dfs(candidate_mask & ~bit_v,
                current_weight,
                chosen_mask)

        # Start search from full set
        full_mask = (1 << n) - 1
        dfs(full_mask, 0, 0)

        # Decode bitmask to sorted list of indices
        result = []
        bm = best_set_mask
        while bm:
            lb = bm & -bm
            idx = lb.bit_length() - 1
            result.append(idx)
            bm ^= lb
        result.sort()
        return result

import sys

class Solver:
    def solve(self, problem, **kwargs):
        sys.setrecursionlimit(10000)
        adj_matrix = problem["adj_matrix"]
        weights = problem["weights"]
        n = len(weights)

        # Precompute neighbor masks and degrees
        neighbor_masks = [0] * n
        degrees = [0] * n
        for i in range(n):
            mask = 0
            deg = 0
            for j, val in enumerate(adj_matrix[i]):
                if val:
                    mask |= 1 << j
                    deg += 1
            neighbor_masks[i] = mask
            degrees[i] = deg

        # Greedy initial solution for bounding
        order = list(range(n))
        order.sort(key=lambda i: weights[i] / (1 + degrees[i]), reverse=True)
        best_weight = 0
        best_set_mask = 0
        greedy_mask = 0
        greedy_weight = 0
        for i in order:
            if not (neighbor_masks[i] & greedy_mask):
                greedy_mask |= 1 << i
                greedy_weight += weights[i]
        best_weight = greedy_weight
        best_set_mask = greedy_mask

        # Branch-and-bound search
        def dfs(candidate_mask, current_weight, chosen_mask):
            nonlocal best_weight, best_set_mask

            # Upper bound: sum of weights of all candidates
            rem = candidate_mask
            rem_sum = 0
            while rem:
                lb = rem & -rem
                idx = lb.bit_length() - 1
                rem_sum += weights[idx]
                rem ^= lb
            if current_weight + rem_sum <= best_weight:
                return

            if candidate_mask == 0:
                if current_weight > best_weight:
                    best_weight = current_weight
                    best_set_mask = chosen_mask
                return

            # Choose candidate with max weight to branch on
            cm = candidate_mask
            max_v = -1
            max_w = -1
            while cm:
                lb = cm & -cm
                idx = lb.bit_length() - 1
                w = weights[idx]
                if w > max_w:
                    max_w = w
                    max_v = idx
                cm ^= lb

            v = max_v
            bit_v = 1 << v

            # Include v
            dfs(candidate_mask & ~neighbor_masks[v] & ~bit_v,
                current_weight + weights[v],
                chosen_mask | bit_v)
            # Exclude v
            dfs(candidate_mask & ~bit_v,
                current_weight,
                chosen_mask)

        full_mask = (1 << n) - 1
        dfs(full_mask, 0, 0)

        # Decode best_set_mask to list of indices
        result = []
        bm = best_set_mask
        while bm:
            lb = bm & -bm
            idx = lb.bit_length() - 1
            result.append(idx)
            bm ^= lb
        result.sort()
        return result

Language Model ✏️ Code Edit
I will replace the entire solver.py with a Numba‐accelerated branch‐and‐bound for up to 64 nodes, and a Python fallback for larger graphs, ensuring correctness while using fast bit‐level operations.

import sys
import numpy as np
from numba import njit

@njit(cache=True, recursive=True)
def dfs_numba(candidate_mask, current_weight, chosen_mask,
              neighbor_masks, weights, best_weight, best_mask):
    # Upper-bound: sum of all candidate weights
    rem = candidate_mask
    rem_sum = 0
    while rem:
        # find index of lowest set bit
        x = rem
        idx = 0
        while (x & 1) == 0:
            x >>= 1
            idx += 1
        rem_sum += weights[idx]
        rem &= rem - 1
    if current_weight + rem_sum <= best_weight[0]:
        return
    # If no candidates left, update best
    if candidate_mask == 0:
        if current_weight > best_weight[0]:
            best_weight[0] = current_weight
            best_mask[0] = chosen_mask
        return
    # Pick candidate with maximum weight
    cm = candidate_mask
    max_v = 0
    max_w = -9223372036854775808  # minimal int64
    while cm:
        x = cm
        idx = 0
        while (x & 1) == 0:
            x >>= 1
            idx += 1
        w = weights[idx]
        if w > max_w:
            max_w = w
            max_v = idx
        cm &= cm - 1
    bit_v = np.uint64(1) << max_v
    # Branch include max_v
    dfs_numba(candidate_mask & (~neighbor_masks[max_v]) & (~bit_v),
              current_weight + weights[max_v],
              chosen_mask | bit_v,
              neighbor_masks, weights, best_weight, best_mask)
    # Branch exclude max_v
    dfs_numba(candidate_mask & (~bit_v),
              current_weight,
              chosen_mask,
              neighbor_masks, weights, best_weight, best_mask)

class Solver:
    def __init__(self):
        # Force JIT compilation of dfs_numba (outside solve timing)
        dummy_masks = np.zeros(1, dtype=np.uint64)
        dummy_weights = np.zeros(1, dtype=np.int64)
        dummy_bw = np.zeros(1, dtype=np.int64)
        dummy_bm = np.zeros(1, dtype=np.uint64)
        dfs_numba(np.uint64(0), 0, np.uint64(0),
                  dummy_masks, dummy_weights,
                  dummy_bw, dummy_bm)

    def solve(self, problem, **kwargs):
        sys.setrecursionlimit(10000)
        adj_matrix = problem["adj_matrix"]
        weights_py = problem["weights"]
        n = len(weights_py)

        # For up to 64 nodes, use the fast Numba bitmask solver
        if n <= 64:
            # Build NumPy arrays
            neighbor_masks = np.zeros(n, dtype=np.uint64)
            for i in range(n):
                m = np.uint64(0)
                row = adj_matrix[i]
                for j, val in enumerate(row):
                    if val:
                        m |= np.uint64(1) << j
                neighbor_masks[i] = m
            weights = np.array(weights_py, dtype=np.int64)

            # Initial greedy bound
            degrees = [int(bin(int(neighbor_masks[i])).count("1")) for i in range(n)]
            order = list(range(n))
            order.sort(key=lambda i: weights_py[i] / (1 + degrees[i]), reverse=True)

            greedy_mask = 0
            greedy_weight = 0
            for i in order:
                if not (greedy_mask & (1 << i)):
                    greedy_mask |= (1 << i)
                    greedy_weight += weights_py[i]
                    greedy_mask |= int(neighbor_masks[i])

            best_weight = np.array([greedy_weight], dtype=np.int64)
            best_mask = np.array([np.uint64(greedy_mask)], dtype=np.uint64)
            full_mask = np.uint64((1 << n) - 1)

            dfs_numba(full_mask, 0, np.uint64(0),
                      neighbor_masks, weights,
                      best_weight, best_mask)

            # Decode mask to list of indices
            res = []
            bm = int(best_mask[0])
            while bm:
                lb = bm & -bm
                idx = lb.bit_length() - 1
                res.append(idx)
                bm ^= lb
            res.sort()
            return res

        # Fallback for larger graphs: pure Python branch & bound (correct, though slower)
        neighbor_masks_py = [0] * n
        degrees_py = [0] * n
        for i in range(n):
            m = 0
            d = 0
            row = adj_matrix[i]
            for j, val in enumerate(row):
                if val:
                    m |= 1 << j
                    d += 1
            neighbor_masks_py[i] = m
            degrees_py[i] = d

        # Greedy initial solution
        order = list(range(n))
        order.sort(key=lambda i: weights_py[i] / (1 + degrees_py[i]), reverse=True)
        best_weight_py = 0
        best_mask_py = 0
        greedy_mask_py = 0
        greedy_weight_py = 0
        for i in order:
            if not (neighbor_masks_py[i] & greedy_mask_py):
                greedy_mask_py |= 1 << i
                greedy_weight_py += weights_py[i]
        best_weight_py = greedy_weight_py
        best_mask_py = greedy_mask_py

        # Recursive DFS in Python
        def dfs_py(cand, curr_w, chosen):
            nonlocal best_weight_py, best_mask_py
            rem = cand
            rem_sum = 0
            while rem:
                lb = rem & -rem
                idx = lb.bit_length() - 1
                rem_sum += weights_py[idx]
                rem ^= lb
            if curr_w + rem_sum <= best_weight_py:
                return
            if cand == 0:
                if curr_w > best_weight_py:
                    best_weight_py = curr_w
                    best_mask_py = chosen
                return
            # pick max weight candidate
            cm = cand
            max_v = -1
            max_w = -1
            while cm:
                lb = cm & -cm
                idx = lb.bit_length() - 1
                if weights_py[idx] > max_w:
                    max_w = weights_py[idx]
                    max_v = idx
                cm ^= lb
            bitv = 1 << max_v
            # include
            dfs_py(cand & ~neighbor_masks_py[max_v] & ~bitv,
                   curr_w + weights_py[max_v],
                   chosen | bitv)
            # exclude
            dfs_py(cand & ~bitv, curr_w, chosen)

        dfs_py((1 << n) - 1, 0, 0)
        # Decode best_mask_py
        res = []
        bm = best_mask_py
        while bm:
            lb = bm & -bm
            idx = lb.bit_length() - 1
            res.append(idx)
            bm ^= lb
        res.sort()
        return res

Replacing the file with a CP‐SAT-based solver with greedy hints for correctness and acceptable speed:

edit
file: solver.py

import sys
from ortools.sat.python import cp_model

class Solver:
    def solve(self, problem, **kwargs):
        adj = problem["adj_matrix"]
        weights = problem["weights"]
        n = len(weights)
        # Build CP‐SAT model
        model = cp_model.CpModel()
        x = [model.NewBoolVar(f"x_{i}") for i in range(n)]
        # Independent‐set constraints
        for i in range(n):
            for j in range(i+1, n):
                if adj[i][j]:
                    model.Add(x[i] + x[j] <= 1)
        # Greedy heuristic for initial hint
        degrees = [sum(adj[i]) for i in range(n)]
        order = list(range(n))
        order.sort(key=lambda i: weights[i] / (1 + degrees[i]), reverse=True)
        chosen = []
        blocked = [False] * n
        for i in order:
            if not blocked[i]:
                chosen.append(i)
                blocked[i] = True
                for j in range(n):
                    if adj[i][j]:
                        blocked[j] = True
        # Provide hint to CP‐SAT
        for i in chosen:
            model.AddHint(x[i], 1)
        # Objective: maximize total weight
        model.Maximize(sum(weights[i] * x[i] for i in range(n)))
        solver = cp_model.CpSolver()
        solver.parameters.num_search_workers = min(8, n)
        status = solver.Solve(model)
        if status in (cp_model.OPTIMAL, cp_model.FEASIBLE):
            return [i for i in range(n) if solver.Value(x[i])]
        # Fallback on greedy if solver fails
        return chosen
---

Language Model ✏️ Code Edit
I’m replacing the CP‐SAT only solver with a fast Numba‐JIT iterative branch‐and‐bound for n≤64, falling back to CP‐SAT only for larger graphs. 

edit
file: solver.py
lines: 1-200
---
import sys
import numpy as np
from numba import njit
from ortools.sat.python import cp_model

@njit(cache=True)
def mwis_nb(n, neighbor_masks, weights):
    # Iterative branch-and-bound for MWIS (bitmask up to 64 nodes)
    stack_cand = np.empty(n, dtype=np.uint64)
    stack_weight = np.empty(n, dtype=np.int64)
    stack_mask = np.empty(n, dtype=np.uint64)
    pos = 0
    best_w = np.int64(0)
    best_mask = np.uint64(0)
    full = np.uint64((1 << n) - 1)
    # initial state
    stack_cand[0] = full
    stack_weight[0] = 0
    stack_mask[0] = np.uint64(0)
    pos = 1
    while pos > 0:
        pos -= 1
        cand = stack_cand[pos]
        cw = stack_weight[pos]
        cmask = stack_mask[pos]
        # Upper-bound: sum of weights of remaining candidates
        rem = cand
        rem_sum = np.int64(0)
        while rem:
            lsb = rem & -rem
            idx = 0
            tmp = lsb
            while (tmp & 1) == 0:
                tmp >>= 1
                idx += 1
            rem_sum += weights[idx]
            rem &= rem - np.uint64(1)
        if cw + rem_sum <= best_w:
            continue
        # If no candidates, update best
        if cand == np.uint64(0):
            if cw > best_w:
                best_w = cw
                best_mask = cmask
            continue
        # Choose vertex of max weight among cand
        cand_bits = cand
        max_v = 0
        max_wt = np.int64(-9223372036854775808)
        while cand_bits:
            lsb2 = cand_bits & -cand_bits
            idx2 = 0
            tmp2 = lsb2
            while (tmp2 & 1) == 0:
                tmp2 >>= 1
                idx2 += 1
            w2 = weights[idx2]
            if w2 > max_wt:
                max_wt = w2
                max_v = idx2
            cand_bits &= cand_bits - np.uint64(1)
        bitv = np.uint64(1) << max_v
        excl = neighbor_masks[max_v] | bitv
        # Exclude branch
        stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~bitv)
        stack_weight[pos] = cw
        stack_mask[pos] = cmask
        pos += 1
        # Include branch
        stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~excl)
        stack_weight[pos] = cw + weights[max_v]
        stack_mask[pos] = cmask | bitv
        pos += 1
    return best_w, best_mask

class Solver:
    def __init__(self):
        # Pre‐compile Numba function (not counted in solve time)
        dummy_masks = np.zeros(1, dtype=np.uint64)
        dummy_weights = np.zeros(1, dtype=np.int64)
        mwis_nb(1, dummy_masks, dummy_weights)

    def solve(self, problem, **kwargs):
        adj = problem["adj_matrix"]
        weights_py = problem["weights"]
        n = len(weights_py)
        # Fast bitmask B&B for small graphs
        if n <= 64:
            # build neighbor masks
            neighbor_masks = np.zeros(n, dtype=np.uint64)
            for i in range(n):
                m = np.uint64(0)
                row = adj[i]
                for j in range(n):
                    if row[j]:
                        m |= np.uint64(1) << j
                neighbor_masks[i] = m
            weights_arr = np.array(weights_py, dtype=np.int64)
            _, bmask = mwis_nb(n, neighbor_masks, weights_arr)
            # extract solution indices
            sol = []
            for i in range(n):
                if bmask & (np.uint64(1) << i):
                    sol.append(i)
            return sol
        # Fallback to CP-SAT for larger graphs
        model = cp_model.CpModel()
        x = [model.NewBoolVar(f"x_{i}") for i in range(n)]
        for i in range(n):
            for j in range(i+1, n):
                if adj[i][j]:
                    model.Add(x[i] + x[j] <= 1)
        model.Maximize(sum(weights_py[i] * x[i] for i in range(n)))
        solver = cp_model.CpSolver()
        solver.parameters.num_search_workers = 1
        status = solver.Solve(model)
        if status == cp_model.OPTIMAL:
            return [i for i in range(n) if solver.Value(x[i])]
        return []
---

> 012:     pos = 0
> 013:     best_w = np.int64(0)
> 014:     best_mask = np.uint64(0)
> 015:     full = np.uint64((1 << n) - 1)
> 016:     # initial state
> 017:     stack_cand[0] = full
> 018:     stack_weight[0] = 0
> 019:     stack_mask[0] = np.uint64(0)
> 020:     pos = 1
> 021:     while pos > 0:
> 022:         pos -= 1
> 023:         cand = stack_cand[pos]
> 024:         cw = stack_weight[pos]
> 025:         cmask = stack_mask[pos]
> 026:         # Upper-bound: sum of weights of remaining candidates
> 027:         rem = cand
> 028:         rem_sum = np.int64(0)
> 029:         while rem:
> 030:             lsb = rem & -rem
> 031:             idx = 0
> 032:             tmp = lsb
> 033:             while (tmp & 1) == 0:
> 034:                 tmp >>= 1
> 035:                 idx += 1
> 036:             rem_sum += weights[idx]
> 037:             rem &= rem - np.uint64(1)
> 038:         if cw + rem_sum <= best_w:
> 039:             continue
> 040:         # If no candidates, update best
> 041:         if cand == np.uint64(0):

> 043:                 best_w = cw
> 044:                 best_mask = cmask
> 045:             continue

> 047:         cand_bits = cand

Creating Cython extension for fast MWIS B&B

# cython: boundscheck=False, wraparound=False, cdivision=True, language_level=3
cimport cython

cpdef tuple mwis_nb(int n, unsigned long long[::1] neighbor_masks, long long[::1] weights):
    """
    Cython-optimized iterative branch-and-bound for Maximum Weighted Independent Set
    on up to 64 nodes. Expects neighbor_masks as uint64 numpy array and
    weights as int64 numpy array (both C-contiguous).
    Returns (best_weight, best_mask).
    """
    cdef unsigned long long full
    if n == 64:
        full = <unsigned long long>-1
    else:
        full = ((<unsigned long long>1 << n) - 1)
    cdef unsigned long long cand, excl, bitv, cmask, rem, lsb, tmp, cand_bits, lsb2
    cdef long long cw, rem_sum, best_w, w2, max_wt
    cdef unsigned long long best_mask
    cdef Py_ssize_t pos = 0
    cdef unsigned long long stack_cand[65]
    cdef unsigned long long stack_mask[65]
    cdef long long stack_weight[65]
    cdef int idx, idx2, max_v

    # initial state
    stack_cand[0] = full
    stack_mask[0] = 0
    stack_weight[0] = 0
    pos = 1
    best_w = 0
    best_mask = 0

    # iterative B&B
    while pos:
        pos -= 1
        cand = stack_cand[pos]
        cw = stack_weight[pos]
        cmask = stack_mask[pos]

        # bound: sum of remaining weights
        rem = cand
        rem_sum = 0
        while rem:
            lsb = rem & -rem
            tmp = lsb
            idx = 0
            while (tmp & 1) == 0:
                tmp >>= 1
                idx += 1
            rem_sum += weights[idx]
            rem &= rem - 1

        if cw + rem_sum <= best_w:
            continue

        # no candidates -> update best
        if cand == 0:
            if cw > best_w:
                best_w = cw
                best_mask = cmask
            continue

        # pick vertex of max weight in cand
        cand_bits = cand
        max_wt = -9223372036854775808  # min int64
        max_v = 0
        while cand_bits:
            lsb2 = cand_bits & -cand_bits
            tmp = lsb2
            idx2 = 0
            while (tmp & 1) == 0:
                tmp >>= 1
                idx2 += 1
            w2 = weights[idx2]
            if w2 > max_wt:
                max_wt = w2
                max_v = idx2
            cand_bits &= cand_bits - 1

        # branch: exclude vs include
        bitv = (<unsigned long long>1 << max_v)
        excl = neighbor_masks[max_v] | bitv

        # exclude branch
        stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~bitv)
        stack_weight[pos] = cw
        stack_mask[pos] = cmask
        pos += 1

        # include branch
        stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~excl)
        stack_weight[pos] = cw + weights[max_v]
        stack_mask[pos] = cmask | bitv
        pos += 1

    return best_w, best_mask

import numpy as np
from ortools.sat.python import cp_model

# Try to use Cython optimized version, fallback to Numba JIT
try:
    from solver_cy import mwis_nb
except ImportError:
    from numba import njit

    @njit(cache=True)
    def mwis_nb(n, neighbor_masks, weights):
        # Iterative branch-and-bound for MWIS (bitmask up to 64 nodes)
        stack_cand = np.empty(n, dtype=np.uint64)
        stack_weight = np.empty(n, dtype=np.int64)
        stack_mask = np.empty(n, dtype=np.uint64)
        best_w = np.int64(0)
        best_mask = np.uint64(0)
        full = np.uint64((1 << n) - 1)
        # initial state
        stack_cand[0] = full
        stack_weight[0] = 0
        stack_mask[0] = np.uint64(0)
        pos = 1
        while pos > 0:
            pos -= 1
            cand = stack_cand[pos]
            cw = stack_weight[pos]
            cmask = stack_mask[pos]
            rem = cand
            rem_sum = np.int64(0)
            while rem:
                lsb = rem & -rem
                idx = 0
                tmp = lsb
                while (tmp & 1) == 0:
                    tmp >>= 1
                    idx += 1
                rem_sum += weights[idx]
                rem &= rem - np.uint64(1)
            if cw + rem_sum <= best_w:
                continue
            if cand == np.uint64(0):
                if cw > best_w:
                    best_w = cw
                    best_mask = cmask
                continue
            cand_bits = cand
            max_v = 0
            max_wt = np.int64(-9223372036854775808)
            while cand_bits:
                lsb2 = cand_bits & -cand_bits
                idx2 = 0
                tmp2 = lsb2
                while (tmp2 & 1) == 0:
                    tmp2 >>= 1
                    idx2 += 1
                w2 = weights[idx2]
                if w2 > max_wt:
                    max_wt = w2
                    max_v = idx2
                cand_bits &= cand_bits - np.uint64(1)
            bitv = np.uint64(1) << max_v
            excl = neighbor_masks[max_v] | bitv
            stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~bitv)
            stack_weight[pos] = cw
            stack_mask[pos] = cmask
            pos += 1
            stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~excl)
            stack_weight[pos] = cw + weights[max_v]
            stack_mask[pos] = cmask | bitv
            pos += 1
        return best_w, best_mask

class Solver:
    def __init__(self):
        # Pre-compile mwis_nb (not counted in solve time)
        dummy_masks = np.zeros(1, dtype=np.uint64)
        dummy_weights = np.zeros(1, dtype=np.int64)
        mwis_nb(1, dummy_masks, dummy_weights)

    def solve(self, problem, **kwargs):
        adj = problem["adj_matrix"]
        weights_py = problem["weights"]
        n = len(weights_py)
        # find connected components
        visited = [False] * n
        sol = []
        for u in range(n):
            if not visited[u]:
                stack = [u]
                visited[u] = True
                comp = []
                while stack:
                    v = stack.pop()
                    comp.append(v)
                    for w in range(n):
                        if adj[v][w] and not visited[w]:
                            visited[w] = True
                            stack.append(w)
                k = len(comp)
                if k == 0:
                    continue
                if k <= 64:
                    neighbor_masks = np.zeros(k, dtype=np.uint64)
                    weights_arr = np.zeros(k, dtype=np.int64)
                    for idx_local, vtx in enumerate(comp):
                        weights_arr[idx_local] = weights_py[vtx]
                        m = np.uint64(0)
                        row = adj[vtx]
                        for jdx_local, wtx in enumerate(comp):
                            if row[wtx]:
                                m |= (np.uint64(1) << jdx_local)
                        neighbor_masks[idx_local] = m
                    _, mask = mwis_nb(k, neighbor_masks, weights_arr)
                    mask_int = int(mask)
                    for idx_local, vtx in enumerate(comp):
                        if (mask_int >> idx_local) & 1:
                            sol.append(vtx)
                else:
                    model = cp_model.CpModel()
                    x = [model.NewBoolVar(f"x_{vtx}") for vtx in comp]
                    for i_local, vtx_i in enumerate(comp):
                        for j_local, vtx_j in enumerate(comp[i_local+1:], start=i_local+1):
                            if adj[vtx_i][vtx_j]:
                                model.Add(x[i_local] + x[j_local] <= 1)
                    model.Maximize(sum(weights_py[vtx] * x[i_local] for i_local, vtx in enumerate(comp)))
                    solver = cp_model.CpSolver()
                    solver.parameters.num_search_workers = 1
                    status = solver.Solve(model)
                    if status == cp_model.OPTIMAL:
                        for i_local, vtx in enumerate(comp):
                            if solver.Value(x[i_local]):
                                sol.append(vtx)
        sol.sort()
        return sol

 1: # cython: boundscheck=False, wraparound=False, cdivision=True, language_level=3
 2: cimport cython
 3: 
 4: cpdef tuple mwis_nb(int n, unsigned long long[::1] neighbor_masks, long long[::1] weights):
 5:     """
 6:     Cython-optimized iterative branch-and-bound for Maximum Weighted Independent Set
 7:     on up to 64 nodes.
 8:     Returns (best_weight, best_mask).
 9:     """
10:     cdef unsigned long long full
11:     if n == 64:
12:         full = <unsigned long long>-1
13:     else:
14:         full = ((<unsigned long long>1 << n) - 1)
15:     cdef unsigned long long cand, excl, bitv, cmask, rem, lsb, tmp, cand_bits, lsb2
16:     cdef long long cw, rem_sum, best_w, w2, max_wt
17:     cdef unsigned long long best_mask
18:     cdef Py_ssize_t pos = 0
19:     cdef unsigned long long stack_cand[65]
20:     cdef unsigned long long stack_mask[65]
21:     cdef long long stack_weight[65]
22:     cdef int idx, idx2, max_v
23: 
24:     # initial state
25:     stack_cand[0] = full
26:     stack_mask[0] = 0
27:     stack_weight[0] = 0
28:     pos = 1
29:     best_w = 0
30:     best_mask = 0
31: 
32:     # iterative B&B
33:     while pos:
34:         pos -= 1
35:         cand = stack_cand[pos]
36:         cw = stack_weight[pos]
37:         cmask = stack_mask[pos]
38: 
39:         # bound: sum of remaining weights
40:         rem = cand
41:         rem_sum = 0
42:         while rem:
43:             lsb = rem & -rem
44:             tmp = lsb
45:             idx = 0
46:             while (tmp & 1) == 0:
47:                 tmp >>= 1
48:                 idx += 1
49:             rem_sum += weights[idx]
50:             rem &= rem - 1
51: 
52:         if cw + rem_sum <= best_w:
53:             continue
54: 
55:         # no candidates -> update best
56:         if cand == 0:
57:             if cw > best_w:
58:                 best_w = cw
59:                 best_mask = cmask
60:             continue
61: 
62:         # pick vertex of max weight in cand
63:         cand_bits = cand
64:         max_wt = -9223372036854775808  # min int64
65:         max_v = 0
66:         while cand_bits:
67:             lsb2 = cand_bits & -cand_bits
68:             tmp = lsb2
69:             idx2 = 0
70:             while (tmp & 1) == 0:
71:                 tmp >>= 1
72:                 idx2 += 1
73:             w2 = weights[idx2]
74:             if w2 > max_wt:
75:                 max_wt = w2
76:                 max_v = idx2
77:             cand_bits &= cand_bits - 1
78: 
79:         # branch: exclude vs include
80:         bitv = (<unsigned long long>1 << max_v)
81:         excl = neighbor_masks[max_v] | bitv
82: 
83:         # exclude branch
84:         stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~bitv)
85:         stack_weight[pos] = cw
86:         stack_mask[pos] = cmask
87:         pos += 1
88: 
89:         # include branch
90:         stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~excl)
91:         stack_weight[pos] = cw + weights[max_v]
92:         stack_mask[pos] = cmask | bitv
93:         pos += 1
94: 
95:     return best_w, best_mask

 10:     @njit(cache=True)
 11:     def mwis_nb(n, neighbor_masks, weights):
 12:         # Iterative branch-and-bound for MWIS (bitmask up to 64 nodes)
 13:         stack_cand = np.empty(n, dtype=np.uint64)
 14:         stack_weight = np.empty(n, dtype=np.int64)
 15:         stack_mask = np.empty(n, dtype=np.uint64)
 16:         best_w = np.int64(0)
 17:         best_mask = np.uint64(0)
 18:         full = np.uint64((1 << n) - 1)
 19:         # initial state
 20:         stack_cand[0] = full
 21:         stack_weight[0] = 0
 22:         stack_mask[0] = np.uint64(0)
 23:         pos = 1
 24:         while pos > 0:
 25:             pos -= 1
 26:             cand = stack_cand[pos]
 27:             cw = stack_weight[pos]
 28:             cmask = stack_mask[pos]
 29:             rem = cand
 30:             rem_sum = np.int64(0)
 31:             while rem:
 32:                 lsb = rem & -rem
 33:                 idx = 0
 34:                 tmp = lsb
 35:                 while (tmp & 1) == 0:
 36:                     tmp >>= 1
 37:                     idx += 1
 38:                 rem_sum += weights[idx]
 39:                 rem &= rem - np.uint64(1)
 40:             if cw + rem_sum <= best_w:
 41:                 continue
 42:             if cand == np.uint64(0):
 43:                 if cw > best_w:
 44:                     best_w = cw
 45:                     best_mask = cmask
 46:                 continue
 47:             cand_bits = cand
 48:             max_v = 0

 50:             while cand_bits:
 51:                 lsb2 = cand_bits & -cand_bits
 52:                 idx2 = 0
 53:                 tmp2 = lsb2
 54:                 while (tmp2 & 1) == 0:
 55:                     tmp2 >>= 1
 56:                     idx2 += 1
 57:                 w2 = weights[idx2]
 58:                 if w2 > max_wt:
 59:                     max_wt = w2
 60:                     max_v = idx2
 61:                 cand_bits &= cand_bits - np.uint64(1)
 62:             bitv = np.uint64(1) << max_v
 63:             excl = neighbor_masks[max_v] | bitv
 64:             stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~bitv)
 65:             stack_weight[pos] = cw
 66:             stack_mask[pos] = cmask
 67:             pos += 1
 68:             stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~excl)
 69:             stack_weight[pos] = cw + weights[max_v]
 70:             stack_mask[pos] = cmask | bitv
 71:             pos += 1
 72:         return best_w, best_mask

 4: cpdef tuple mwis_nb(int n, unsigned long long[::1] neighbor_masks, long long[::1] weights):
 5:     """
 6:     Cython-optimized iterative branch-and-bound for Maximum Weighted Independent Set
 7:     on up to 64 nodes.
 8:     Returns (best_weight, best_mask).
 9:     """
10:     cdef unsigned long long full
11:     if n == 64:
12:         full = <unsigned long long>-1
13:     else:
14:         full = ((<unsigned long long>1 << n) - 1)
15:     cdef unsigned long long cand, excl, bitv, cmask, rem, lsb, tmp, cand_bits, lsb2
16:     cdef long long cw, rem_sum, best_w, w2, max_wt
17:     cdef unsigned long long best_mask
18:     cdef Py_ssize_t pos = 0
19:     cdef unsigned long long stack_cand[65]
20:     cdef unsigned long long stack_mask[65]
21:     cdef long long stack_weight[65]
22:     cdef int idx, idx2, max_v
23: 
24:     # initial state
25:     stack_cand[0] = full
26:     stack_mask[0] = 0
27:     stack_weight[0] = 0
28:     pos = 1
29:     best_w = 0
30:     best_mask = 0
31: 
32:     # iterative B&B
33:     while pos:
34:         pos -= 1
35:         cand = stack_cand[pos]
36:         cw = stack_weight[pos]
37:         cmask = stack_mask[pos]
38: 
39:         # bound: sum of remaining weights
40:         rem = cand
41:         rem_sum = 0
42:         while rem:
43:             lsb = rem & -rem
44:             tmp = lsb
45:             idx = 0
46:             while (tmp & 1) == 0:
47:                 tmp >>= 1
48:                 idx += 1
49:             rem_sum += weights[idx]
50:             rem &= rem - 1
51: 
52:         if cw + rem_sum <= best_w:
53:             continue
54: 
55:         # no candidates -> update best
56:         if cand == 0:
57:             if cw > best_w:
58:                 best_w = cw
59:                 best_mask = cmask
60:             continue
61: 
62:         # pick vertex of max weight in cand
63:         cand_bits = cand
64:         max_wt = -9223372036854775808  # min int64
65:         max_v = 0
66:         while cand_bits:
67:             lsb2 = cand_bits & -cand_bits
68:             tmp = lsb2
69:             idx2 = 0
70:             while (tmp & 1) == 0:
71:                 tmp >>= 1
72:                 idx2 += 1
73:             w2 = weights[idx2]
74:             if w2 > max_wt:
75:                 max_wt = w2
76:                 max_v = idx2
77:             cand_bits &= cand_bits - 1
78: 
79:         # branch: exclude vs include
80:         bitv = (<unsigned long long>1 << max_v)
81:         excl = neighbor_masks[max_v] | bitv
82: 
83:         # exclude branch
84:         stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~bitv)
85:         stack_weight[pos] = cw
86:         stack_mask[pos] = cmask
87:         pos += 1
88: 
89:         # include branch
90:         stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~excl)
91:         stack_weight[pos] = cw + weights[max_v]
92:         stack_mask[pos] = cmask | bitv
93:         pos += 1
94: 
95:     return best_w, best_mask

    # Greedy initial solution for bound
    gre_cand = full
    gre_mask = 0
    gre_w = 0
    while gre_cand:
        greedy_bits = gre_cand
        greedy_max_wt = <long long>-9223372036854775808
        greedy_max_v = 0
        # find highest-weight vertex
        while greedy_bits:
            lsb = greedy_bits & -greedy_bits
            tmp = lsb
            idx = 0
            while (tmp & 1) == 0:
                tmp >>= 1
                idx += 1
            w2 = weights[idx]
            if w2 > greedy_max_wt:
                greedy_max_wt = w2
                greedy_max_v = idx
            greedy_bits &= greedy_bits - 1
        bitv = (<unsigned long long>1 << greedy_max_v)
        gre_mask |= bitv
        gre_w += weights[greedy_max_v]
        gre_cand &= ~ (neighbor_masks[greedy_max_v] | bitv)
    best_w = gre_w
    best_mask = gre_mask

 12:         # Iterative branch-and-bound for MWIS (bitmask up to 64 nodes)
 13:         stack_cand = np.empty(n, dtype=np.uint64)
 14:         stack_weight = np.empty(n, dtype=np.int64)
 15:         stack_mask = np.empty(n, dtype=np.uint64)

 18:         full = np.uint64((1 << n) - 1)
 19:         # initial state
 20:         stack_cand[0] = full
 21:         stack_weight[0] = 0
 22:         stack_mask[0] = np.uint64(0)
 23:         pos = 1
 24:         while pos > 0:
 25:             pos -= 1
 26:             cand = stack_cand[pos]

 28:             cmask = stack_mask[pos]

 30:             rem_sum = np.int64(0)
 31:             while rem:
 32:                 lsb = rem & -rem
 33:                 idx = 0
 34:                 tmp = lsb
 35:                 while (tmp & 1) == 0:
 36:                     tmp >>= 1
 37:                     idx += 1
 38:                 rem_sum += weights[idx]
 39:                 rem &= rem - np.uint64(1)

 41:                 continue

 80: 
 81:     def solve(self, problem, **kwargs):
 82:         adj = problem["adj_matrix"]
 83:         weights_py = problem["weights"]
 84:         n = len(weights_py)
 85:         # find connected components
 86:         visited = [False] * n
 87:         sol = []
 88:         for u in range(n):
 89:             if not visited[u]:
 90:                 stack = [u]
 91:                 visited[u] = True
 92:                 comp = []
 93:                 while stack:
 94:                     v = stack.pop()
 95:                     comp.append(v)
 96:                     for w in range(n):
 97:                         if adj[v][w] and not visited[w]:
 98:                             visited[w] = True
 99:                             stack.append(w)
100:                 k = len(comp)
101:                 if k == 0:
102:                     continue
103:                 if k <= 64:
104:                     neighbor_masks = np.zeros(k, dtype=np.uint64)
105:                     weights_arr = np.zeros(k, dtype=np.int64)
106:                     for idx_local, vtx in enumerate(comp):
107:                         weights_arr[idx_local] = weights_py[vtx]
108:                         m = np.uint64(0)
109:                         row = adj[vtx]
110:                         for jdx_local, wtx in enumerate(comp):
111:                             if row[wtx]:
112:                                 m |= np.uint64(1 << jdx_local)
113:                         neighbor_masks[idx_local] = m
114:                     _, mask = mwis_nb(k, neighbor_masks, weights_arr)
115:                     mask_int = int(mask)
116:                     for idx_local, vtx in enumerate(comp):
117:                         if (mask_int >> idx_local) & 1:
118:                             sol.append(vtx)
119:                 else:
120:                     model = cp_model.CpModel()
121:                     x = [model.NewBoolVar(f"x_{vtx}") for vtx in comp]
122:                     for i_local, vtx_i in enumerate(comp):
123:                         for j_local, vtx_j in enumerate(comp[i_local+1:], start=i_local+1):
124:                             if adj[vtx_i][vtx_j]:
125:                                 model.Add(x[i_local] + x[j_local] <= 1)
126:                     model.Maximize(sum(weights_py[vtx] * x[i_local] for i_local, vtx in enumerate(comp)))
127:                     solver = cp_model.CpSolver()
128:                     solver.parameters.num_search_workers = 1
129:                     status = solver.Solve(model)
130:                     if status == cp_model.OPTIMAL:
131:                         for i_local, vtx in enumerate(comp):
132:                             if solver.Value(x[i_local]):
133:                                 sol.append(vtx)
134:         sol.sort()
135:         return sol
136:         return []

Language Model ✏️ Code Edit
Implement a CP-SAT solver seeded with a fast greedy hint:

edit
file: solver.py
lines: 1-0
---
from ortools.sat.python import cp_model

class Solver:
    def solve(self, problem, **kwargs):
        adj = problem["adj_matrix"]
        weights = problem["weights"]
        n = len(adj)
        # Build neighbor sets
        neigh = [set() for _ in range(n)]
        for i in range(n):
            for j in range(n):
                if adj[i][j]:
                    neigh[i].add(j)
        # Greedy initial independent set by descending weight
        idx_sorted = sorted(range(n), key=lambda x: -weights[x])
        greedy_sol = []
        forbidden = set()
        for v in idx_sorted:
            if v not in forbidden:
                greedy_sol.append(v)
                forbidden.add(v)
                forbidden |= neigh[v]
        # CP-SAT model
        model = cp_model.CpModel()
        vars = [model.NewBoolVar(f"x{i}") for i in range(n)]
        # Independence constraints
        for i in range(n):
            for j in range(i + 1, n):
                if adj[i][j]:
                    model.Add(vars[i] + vars[j] <= 1)
        # Objective
        model.Maximize(sum(weights[i] * vars[i] for i in range(n)))
        # Provide greedy hint
        for i in range(n):
            model.AddHint(vars[i], 1 if i in greedy_sol else 0)
        solver = cp_model.CpSolver()
        solver.parameters.num_search_workers = 8
        status = solver.Solve(model)
        if status in (cp_model.OPTIMAL, cp_model.FEASIBLE):
            return [i for i in range(n) if solver.Value(vars[i]) == 1]
        # Fallback
        return greedy_sol
---

 11:     def mwis_nb(n, neighbor_masks, weights):
 12:         # Iterative branch-and-bound for MWIS (bitmask up to 64 nodes)
 13:         stack_cand = np.empty(n, dtype=np.uint64)
 14:         stack_weight = np.empty(n, dtype=np.int64)
 15:         stack_mask = np.empty(n, dtype=np.uint64)
 16:         best_w = np.int64(0)
 17:         best_mask = np.uint64(0)
 18:         full = np.uint64((1 << n) - 1)
 19:         # initial state
 20:         stack_cand[0] = full
 21:         stack_weight[0] = 0
 22:         stack_mask[0] = np.uint64(0)
 23:         pos = 1
 24:         while pos > 0:
 25:             pos -= 1
 26:             cand = stack_cand[pos]
 27:             cw = stack_weight[pos]
 28:             cmask = stack_mask[pos]
 29:             rem = cand
 30:             rem_sum = np.int64(0)
 31:             while rem:
 32:                 lsb = rem & -rem
 33:                 idx = 0
 34:                 tmp = lsb
 35:                 while (tmp & 1) == 0:
 36:                     tmp >>= 1
 37:                     idx += 1
 38:                 rem_sum += weights[idx]
 39:                 rem &= rem - np.uint64(1)
 40:             if cw + rem_sum <= best_w:
 41:                 continue
 42:             if cand == np.uint64(0):
 43:                 if cw > best_w:
 44:                     best_w = cw
 45:                     best_mask = cmask
 46:                 continue
 47:             cand_bits = cand
 48:             max_v = 0
 49:             max_wt = np.int64(-9223372036854775808)
 50:             while cand_bits:
 51:                 lsb2 = cand_bits & -cand_bits
 52:                 idx2 = 0
 53:                 tmp2 = lsb2
 54:                 while (tmp2 & 1) == 0:
 55:                     tmp2 >>= 1
 56:                     idx2 += 1
 57:                 w2 = weights[idx2]
 58:                 if w2 > max_wt:
 59:                     max_wt = w2
 60:                     max_v = idx2
 61:                 cand_bits &= cand_bits - np.uint64(1)
 62:             bitv = np.uint64(1) << max_v
 63:             excl = neighbor_masks[max_v] | bitv
 64:             stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~bitv)
 65:             stack_weight[pos] = cw
 66:             stack_mask[pos] = cmask
 67:             pos += 1
 68:             stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~excl)
 69:             stack_weight[pos] = cw + weights[max_v]
 70:             stack_mask[pos] = cmask | bitv
 71:             pos += 1
 72:         return best_w, best_mask
 73: 
 74: class Solver:
 75:     def __init__(self):
 76:         # Pre-compile mwis_nb (not counted in solve time)
 77:         dummy_masks = np.zeros(1, dtype=np.uint64)
 78:         dummy_weights = np.zeros(1, dtype=np.int64)
 79:         mwis_nb(1, dummy_masks, dummy_weights)
 80: 
 81:     def solve(self, problem, **kwargs):
 82:         adj = problem["adj_matrix"]
 83:         weights_py = problem["weights"]
 84:         n = len(weights_py)
 85:         # find connected components
 86:         visited = [False] * n
 87:         sol = []
 88:         for u in range(n):
 89:             if not visited[u]:
 90:                 stack = [u]
 91:                 visited[u] = True
 92:                 comp = []
 93:                 while stack:
 94:                     v = stack.pop()
 95:                     comp.append(v)
 96:                     for w in range(n):
 97:                         if adj[v][w] and not visited[w]:
 98:                             visited[w] = True
 99:                             stack.append(w)
100:                 k = len(comp)
...

102:                     continue

113:                         neighbor_masks[idx_local] = m

115:                     mask_int = int(mask)

117:                         if (mask_int >> idx_local) & 1:
118:                             sol.append(vtx)
119:                 else:
120:                     model = cp_model.CpModel()

122:                     for i_local, vtx_i in enumerate(comp):
123:                         for j_local, vtx_j in enumerate(comp[i_local+1:], start=i_local+1):
124:                             if adj[vtx_i][vtx_j]:
125:                                 model.Add(x[i_local] + x[j_local] <= 1)
126:                     model.Maximize(sum(weights_py[vtx] * x[i_local] for i_local, vtx in enumerate(comp)))
127:                     solver = cp_model.CpSolver()
128:                     solver.parameters.num_search_workers = 1
129:                     status = solver.Solve(model)
130:                     if status == cp_model.OPTIMAL:
131:                         for i_local, vtx in enumerate(comp):
132:                             if solver.Value(x[i_local]):
133:                                 sol.append(vtx)
134:         sol.sort()
135:         return sol
136:         return []

Language Model ✏️ Code Edit
Removing the expensive max‐weight scan and using a single trailing‐zero pivot pick:

file: solver.py

            # pivot selection: single trailing‐zero bit (fast)
            lsb2 = cand & -cand
            idx2 = 0
            tmp2 = lsb2
            while (tmp2 & 1) == 0:
                tmp2 >>= 1
                idx2 += 1
            bitv = np.uint64(1) << idx2
            excl = neighbor_masks[idx2] | bitv
            # branch without this vertex
            stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~bitv)
            stack_weight[pos] = cw
            stack_mask[pos] = cmask
            pos += 1
            # branch with this vertex
            stack_cand[pos] = cand & (~excl)
            stack_weight[pos] = cw + weights[idx2]
            stack_mask[pos] = cmask | bitv
            pos += 1
